headline.main: The Yellow Fever in Philadelphia--confirmed Case and Death.

docs.lead_paragraph: From the Evening Journal of yesterday. A death from bona fide yellow fever has taken place in Philadelphia, and being opposed to secresy in such matters, we have no hesitation in making it public. headline.main: LATER FROM HAVANA.; Arrival of the Philadelphia.

docs.lead_paragraph: The U. S. Mail steamship Philadelphia, ALFRED G. GRAY, Commander, arrived at this port yesterday morning. She left New-Orleans at 9 A. M., of the 20th, for New York, via Havana, arrived at the latter port on the morning of the 23d, and sailed again at noon of the same day.

docs.lead_paragraph: Mrs. EVA COPENHAGEN, who died recently in smythe County, Va., aged 88 years, leaves one hundred and five grand children, one hundred and thirty great grand children, and one great great grand child. Georgia papers announce the death of General THOMAS FLOURNOY, as his residence on the Sand Hills, Gen, FLOURNOY, says the Augusta Chronicle, was a man of a former generation.
